DESCRIPTION:THE PURPOSE OF THIS AMERICAN RESCUE PLAN-FUNDED GRANT IS TO DEVELOP A WATER QUALITY PROTECTION PROGRAM AND CLEAN WATER EDUCATION PROGRAM IN RESPONSE TO THE IMPACTS OF MINING OPERATIONS ON THE SOLE SOURCE DRINKING WATER SUPPLY WITHIN THE CHICKASAW NATION (CN) TREATY TERRITORY, ARBUCKLE SIMPSON AQUIFER (ASA). IMPACTS OF THESE MINING OPERATIONS INCLUDE THE DISCHARGE OF LARGE VOLUMES OF AQUIFER WATER AND THE INTRODUCTION OF SAND AND CONTAMINANTS INTO ASA AND ITS EMANATING SPRINGS AT A LEVEL POTENTIALLY OUT OF COMPLIANCE WITH SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT CRITERIA, THREATENING HUMAN HEALTH. THE PROJECT WILL IMPROVE TRIBAL AND BROADER COMMUNITY UNDERSTANDING OF ENVIRONMENTAL AND PUBLIC HEALTH ISSUES AND IMPACTS RELATED TO DRINKING WATER SUSTAINABILITY, STRENGTHEN PUBLIC PARTICIPATION AND COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT THROUGH CITIZEN SCIENCE WATER QUALITY MONITORING AND EDUCATION ACTIVITIES, AND DEVELOP STRONG TECHNICAL PARTNERSHIPS TO ADDRESS WATER QUALITY CONCERNS WITHIN THE SOLE SOURCE WATER SUPPLY.ACTIVITIES:THE CHICKASAW NATION (CN) WILL USE GIS TO DETERMINE THE MINING FOOTPRINT OVER ARBUCKLE SIMPSON AQUIFER (ASA), INCLUDING WHICH COMMUNITY WATER SUPPLIES ARE IMPACTED BY DISCHARGE FLOW PATHS AND POTENTIAL POLLUTANT CONTAMINATION. IN COLLABORATION WITH EPA'S KERR ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH CENTER, THE OKLAHOMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (ODEQ), AND THE OKA INSTITUTE AT EAST CENTRAL UNIVERSITY (ECU), CN WILL WORK WITH A TECHNICAL TEAM TO FORMULATE A PLAN FOR AND EXECUTE A WATER QUALITY SAMPLING PROGRAM FOR MINING DISCHARGE AFFECTING ASA. ADDITIONALLY, CN WILL PARTNER WITH THE OKA INSTITUTE TO ENGAGE THE PUBLIC IN PROJECT IMPLEMENTATION BY: 1) FORMING A COALITION OF TRIBAL CITIZENS, ECU STUDENTS,  AND OTHER COMMUNITY MEMBERS TO PARTICIPATE IN A CITIZEN SCIENCE WATER QUALITY MONITORING PROGRAM FOR ASA, INCLUDING EDUCATIONAL ACTIVITIES AND HANDS-ON OUTREACH; AND 2) INCORPORATING DISCUSSION OF THE PROJECT, INCLUDING ASA, ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE, AND COMMUNITY IMPACTS OF DRINKING WATER SUSTAINABILITY, INTO THE OKA INSTITUTE'S ANNUAL SUSTAINABILITY CONFERENCE.    
SUBRECIPIENT:THE SUBAWARDEE, EAST CENTRAL UNIVERSITY (ECU) OKA INSTITUTE, WILL BE THE PRIMARY IMPLEMENTER OF THE PUBLIC PARTICIPATION ASPECT OF THE SOLE SOURCE DRINKING WATER PROJECT. OKA INSTITUTE, IN PARTNERSHIP WITH THE CHICKASAW NATION (CN), WILL ORGANIZE MEETINGS AND CHAMPION STAKEHOLDER ENGAGEMENT AND OUTREACH, WHICH WILL INCLUDE: 
1) DEVELOPING A BROAD COALITION OF TRIBAL MEMBERS, ECU STAFF AND STUDENTS, LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL ORGANIZATIONS, AND OTHER MEMBERS OF THE COMMUNITY TO ENGAGE IN THE PROJECT; 
2) WORKING CLOSELY WITH TRIBAL COMMUNITIES AND LANDOWNERS TO IDENTIFY AND DEVELOP CITIZEN SCIENCE EDUCATION AND ACTION IN THE FIELD;
3) PROVIDING TRAINING IN FIELD MONITORING TECHNIQUES AND REPORTING AND OVERSEEING THE CITIZEN SCIENCE WATER QUALITY MONITORING PROGRAM;
4) DEVELOPING AND DELIVERING MATERIALS TO TRIBAL COMMUNITIES THROUGHOUT THE LIFE OF THE PROJECT; AND
5) ORGANIZING AND COORDINATING A SUSTAINABILITY CONFERENCE TO HIGHLIGHT THE WATER SUSTAINABILITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE ACTIVITIES OCCURRING WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS GRANT PROJECT.

THE OKA INSTITUTE WILL ALSO WORK WITH CN TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE WITH THE TERMS AND CONDITIONS OF THE GRANT AGREEMENT AND DEVELOP A FINAL COMPREHENSIVE REPORT ON THE PROJECT.
OUTCOMES:THE DELIVERABLES FOR THIS PROJECT INCLUDE GIS MAPPING OF MINING ACTIVITY AND IMPACTS OCCURRING OVER THE ARBUCKLE SIMPSON AQUIFER (ASA), AN APPROVED QAPP FOR THE ASA MINING DISCHARGE WATER QUALITY SAMPLING PROGRAM, AND A FINAL COMPREHENSIVE REPORT DETAILING OUTCOMES OF THE CITIZEN SCIENCE WATER QUALITY MONITORING PROGRAM AND THE MINING DISCHARGE WATER QUALITY SAMPLING PROGRAM. EXPECTED OUTCOMES INCLUDE A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE HUMAN HEALTH IMPACTS OF MINING OPERATIONS ON ASA, ESTABLISHMENT OF SUSTAINABLE PARTNERSHIPS AND APPROACHES TO ADDRESSING DRINKING WATER POLLUTANTS ENTERING PUBLIC WATER SUPPLIES, AND IMPROVED TRIBAL AND OT

DESCRIPTION:THE WESTERN ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE CENTER FOR ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE (WEST EJ CENTER) OR ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE THRIVING COMMUNITIES TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE CENTER (EJ TCTAC) WILL BE LED BY THE GRANTEE, ARIZONA BOARD OF REGENTS, THE UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA, THROUGH A CENTRAL HUB (CH) WITH VARIOUS UNITS AS WELL AS THE SUBWARDEE, SONORA ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH INSTITUTE, TO SUPPORT ALL REGION 9 COMMUNITIES WITH TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FOR DEVELOPING, APPLYING FOR, AND SUCCESSFULLY MANAGING ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE PROJECTS AND GRANTS. OTHER PARTNERS INCLUDE PUBLIC HEALTH INSTITUTE, HAWAI'I PUBLIC HEALTH INSTITUTE, UNIVERSITY OF NEVADA, RENO AND UNIVERSITY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, THAT WILL SUPPORT THE CH WITH MARKETING AND OUTREACH, TRAINING DEVELOPMENT, PROGRAM EVALUATION, AND TRIBAL ASSISTANCE. THE THREE MAIN OBJECTIVES ARE: 1) PROVIDING ASSISTANCE AND TRAINING FOR GRANT APPLICATIONS AND MANAGEMENT; 2); INCREASING COMMUNITY INVOLVEMENT IN ENVIRONMENTAL AND ENERGY DECISION-MAKING AND 3) PROVIDING ACCESS TO ENVIRONMENTAL AND ENERGY EXPERTISE. CH AND SPOKE PARTNERS WILL LEAD ON DELIVERING SERVICES (IN PERSON AND VIRTUALLY) TO ELIGIBLE COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS, BUILDING AND EXPANDING ON THEIR EXISTING ELIGIBLE COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS IN THEIR NETWORK AND IDENTIFYING AND CONNECTING WITH NEW COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS, SUPPORTING COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT AND CAPACITY BUILDING.

THIS AGREEMENT PROVIDES PARTIAL FUNDING IN THE AMOUNT OF $4,000,000. PREAWARD COSTS ARE APPROVED BACK TO 6/1/2023. REFER TO TERMS AND CONDITIONS.ACTIVITIES:KEY ACTIVITIES PERFORMED ARE AS FOLLOWS: 
1) DEVELOPMENT OF THE WEST EJ TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE CENTER, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO HIRING AND TRAINING, PARTNER COORDINATION, PARTICIPANT SUPPORT, GRANT MANAGEMENT, AND EPA REPORTING;
2) DEVELOPMENT AND MANAGEMENT OF SUBAWARD CONTRACTS;
3) DEVELOPMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF A MARKETING AND OUTREACH PLAN REACHING ALL OF REGION 9;
4) COORDINATION AND EXECUTION OF A NEEDS ASSESSMENT ACROSS REGION 9, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO DATA ANALYSIS AND PLANNING SESSIONS FOR HOW TO ADDRESS COMMUNITY NEEDS;
5) DESIGNING AN EVALUATION PLAN TO RECEIVE AND INCORPORATE PARTICIPANT FEEDBACK IN CENTER ACTIVITIES;
6) DEVELOPMENT AND EXECUTION OF TRAININGS FOR IDENTIFYING AND APPLYING TO FUNDING SOURCES FOR ENVIRONMENTAL AND ENERGY PROJECTS, AS WELL AS ENERGY RESILIENCE TRAININGS;
7) DEVELOPMENT OF ONLINE FUNDING REPOSITORY AS WELL AS SUMMARY OF RENEWABLE AND ENERGY POLICES AND ENERGY FINANCING OPTIONS WHICH WILL BE LOCATED ON THE ESTABLISHED WEBSITE FOR THE TCTAC IN ENGLISH AND SPANISH;
8) FOSTERING COMMUNITY INVOLVEMENT AND CAPACITY BUILDING THROUGH ACTIVITIES SUCH AS COMMUNITY RESOURCE FAIRS, COMMUNITY CHAMPIONS PROGRAM, AND STUDENT INTERNSHIPS;
9) DEVELOPMENT OF TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE CONSULTATION PROCESSES FOR COMMUNITY MEMBERS, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO COMPILATION OF TECHNICAL RESOURCES, DEVELOPMENT OF USER GUIDES, STATISTICAL CONSULTATION, AND HANDS ON ASSISTANCE FOR SUBMITTING AND POST-AWARD MANAGEMENT COMPLIANCE.SUBRECIPIENT:EACH SPOKE WILL HAVE A SUBWARD WORKPLAN AND BUDGET ASSIGNED THAT IS APPROVED AND MANAGED BY THE GRANTEE ACCORDING TO UA POLICIES FOR SUBAWARDS (HTTPS://RESEARCH.ARIZONA.EDU/ADMINISTRATION/SUBAWARDS-OUTGOING). ARIZONA BOARD OF REGENTS, THE UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA WILL REPORT UPDATES ON SUBWARDS TO EPA PO IN QUARTERLY REPORTS AND SHARE ANY ISSUES THEY HAVE AND NEED SUPPORT WITH.  THE ARIZONA BOARD OF REGENTS, THE UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA WILL HAVE REVIEWED THE BUDGETS FOR UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA AND THE TCTAC PARTNERS AS SUBAWARDS TO ENSURE THAT ALL AWARDS MEET THE SPECIFIED REQUIREMENTS OF ALLOWABILITY, ALLOCABILITY, AND REASONABLENESS WITH THE TERMS AND CONDITIONS OF THIS EPA GRANT.

